{
  "What are the monomer building blocks of proteins?": "",
  "Amino acids": "",
  "Monosaccharides": "",
  "Nucleotides": "",
  "Fatty acids": "",
  "Proteins are polymers of amino acids. There are 20 common amino acids, each with a central carbon bonded to an amino group, carboxyl group, hydrogen atom, and a variable R group (side chain).": "",
  "What type of bond links amino acids together in a polypeptide chain?": "",
  "Peptide bond": "",
  "Glycosidic bond": "",
  "Phosphodiester bond": "",
  "Ester bond": "",
  "Peptide bonds form through dehydration synthesis between the carboxyl group of one amino acid and the amino group of the next, creating a covalent C-N linkage and releasing water.": "",
  "Which level of protein structure refers to the linear sequence of amino acids?": "",
  "Tertiary structure": "",
  "Primary structure": "",
  "Quaternary structure": "",
  "Secondary structure": "",
  "Primary structure is the unique sequence of amino acids in a polypeptide chain, determined by the gene encoding it. This sequence dictates all higher levels of protein structure.": "",
  "Alpha helices and beta pleated sheets are examples of which level of protein structure?": "",
  "Secondary structure consists of local folding patterns stabilized by hydrogen bonds between backbone atoms. Alpha helices are coiled and beta pleated sheets are zigzag folded arrangements.": "",
  "What primarily determines the tertiary structure of a protein?": "",
  "The number of polypeptide subunits": "",
  "Interactions among R groups including hydrophobic interactions, ionic bonds, hydrogen bonds, and disulfide bridges": "",
  "Hydrogen bonds between backbone amino and carboxyl groups only": "",
  "Only covalent peptide bonds between amino acids": "",
  "Tertiary structure is the overall 3D shape of a single polypeptide, determined by interactions among R groups: hydrophobic interactions, hydrogen bonds, ionic bonds, van der Waals forces, and covalent disulfide bridges.": "",
  "Hemoglobin consists of four polypeptide subunits. This describes which level of protein structure?": "",
  "Tertiary": "",
  "Quaternary": "",
  "Primary": "",
  "Secondary": "",
  "Quaternary structure refers to the arrangement of two or more polypeptide subunits into a functional protein complex. Hemoglobin has four subunits (two alpha and two beta chains) that work together cooperatively.": "",
  "What happens to a protein when it is denatured?": "",
  "Its amino acid sequence is permanently altered": "",
  "Its peptide bonds are broken and amino acids are released": "",
  "It gains a new function": "",
  "Its three-dimensional shape is disrupted, but primary structure remains intact": "",
  "Denaturation unfolds the protein's 3D structure by disrupting noncovalent interactions (and sometimes disulfide bridges), but peptide bonds remain intact. The loss of shape typically destroys the protein's biological function.": "",
  "Which part of an amino acid determines its unique chemical properties?": "",
  "The R group (side chain)": "",
  "The amino group": "",
  "The carboxyl group": "",
  "The central alpha carbon": "",
  "The R group (side chain) varies among the 20 amino acids and determines whether the amino acid is polar, nonpolar, acidic, or basic. This diversity in R groups drives protein folding and function.": "",
  "Which type of covalent bond between cysteine residues helps stabilize the tertiary structure of some proteins?": "",
  "Disulfide bridge": "",
  "Hydrogen bond": "",
  "Ionic bond": "",
  "Disulfide bridges (S-S bonds) form between the sulfhydryl groups of two cysteine residues. These strong covalent bonds significantly stabilize a protein's tertiary structure, especially in secreted proteins.": "",
  "How many different amino acids are commonly found in proteins?": "",
  "64": "",
  "20": "",
  "12": "",
  "4": "",
  "There are 20 standard amino acids encoded by the genetic code. These differ only in their R groups, which range from simple (glycine has just a hydrogen) to complex (tryptophan has an indole ring).": "",
  "What is a peptide bond?": "",
  "A hydrogen bond between the R groups of two amino acids": "",
  "An ionic bond between a positively charged and negatively charged amino acid": "",
  "A bond between a protein and a carbohydrate molecule": "",
  "A covalent bond formed by dehydration synthesis between the carboxyl group of one amino acid and the amino group of the next": "",
  "A peptide bond is a covalent C-N bond formed between the carboxyl group (-COOH) of one amino acid and the amino group (-NH₂) of the next during a dehydration synthesis reaction that releases water.": "",
  "What does 'denaturation' mean with respect to proteins?": "",
  "The addition of a phosphate group to a protein, particularly in the context of denaturation": "",
  "The synthesis of a new protein from amino acids in most scenarios involving denaturation factors": "",
  "The loss of a protein's three-dimensional shape due to disruption of noncovalent bonds and sometimes disulfide bridges, resulting in loss of function": "",
  "The permanent change of a protein's amino acid sequence under most circumstances involving denaturation": "",
  "Denaturation is the unfolding of a protein caused by factors like extreme heat, pH changes, or chemical agents. It disrupts the protein's higher-order structure (secondary, tertiary, quaternary) while leaving the primary sequence intact.": "",
  "What is an enzyme?": "",
  "A nucleic acid that carries genetic information": "",
  "A protein (or occasionally RNA) catalyst that speeds up chemical reactions by lowering activation energy without being consumed": "",
  "A lipid molecule that stores energy in cells": "",
  "A carbohydrate that provides structural support": "",
  "Enzymes are biological catalysts, mostly proteins, that accelerate chemical reactions by lowering the activation energy. They are highly specific, reusable, and essential for virtually all metabolic processes.": "",
  "What does 'R group' mean in amino acid chemistry?": "",
  "The regulatory region of a protein that controls its activity": "",
  "The repeating backbone unit shared by all amino acids": "",
  "The recognition site where enzymes bind substrates": "",
  "The variable side chain attached to the central carbon that differs among the 20 amino acids and determines each amino acid's unique properties": "",
  "The R group (side chain) is the variable portion of an amino acid that distinguishes one from another. R groups can be nonpolar, polar uncharged, positively charged, or negatively charged, and they drive protein folding and interactions.": "",
  "What is a polypeptide?": "",
  "A polymer of nucleotides linked by phosphodiester bonds": "",
  "A polymer of fatty acids linked by ester bonds": "",
  "A chain of monosaccharides linked by glycosidic bonds": "",
  "A chain of amino acids linked together by peptide bonds": "",
  "A polypeptide is a linear chain of amino acids joined by peptide bonds. A functional protein may consist of one or more polypeptides that fold into specific three-dimensional shapes.": "",
  "What does 'quaternary structure' refer to in proteins?": "",
  "The overall 3D shape of a single polypeptide chain": "",
  "The local folding patterns like alpha helices and beta sheets": "",
  "The sequence of amino acids in a single polypeptide": "",
  "The arrangement and interaction of two or more polypeptide subunits in a multi-subunit protein complex": "",
  "Quaternary structure describes how multiple polypeptide chains (subunits) assemble and interact to form a functional protein. Not all proteins have quaternary structure; it only applies to multi-subunit proteins like hemoglobin.": "",
  "What is a 'chaperone protein'?": "",
  "A protein that assists other proteins in folding correctly and prevents misfolding or aggregation": "",
  "A protein that breaks down misfolded proteins into amino acids": "",
  "A regulatory protein that controls gene expression": "",
  "A transport protein that moves lipids through the bloodstream": "",
  "Chaperone proteins (chaperonins) assist newly synthesized polypeptides in folding into their correct 3D conformations. They provide a protected environment that prevents inappropriate interactions and aggregation.": "",
  "What does the term 'active site' mean?": "",
  "The site where an enzyme is synthesized on the ribosome": "",
  "The specific region on an enzyme where the substrate binds and the catalytic reaction takes place": "",
  "Any region of a protein that contains alpha helices": "",
  "The entire surface area of an enzyme": "",
  "The active site is a specific pocket or groove on an enzyme's surface where the substrate binds through complementary shape and chemical interactions. The enzyme catalyzes the reaction at this site and then releases the product.": "",
  "What is a 'disulfide bridge'?": "",
  "A hydrogen bond between two sulfur-containing amino acids": "",
  "A covalent bond formed between the sulfhydryl groups (-SH) of two cysteine residues, helping stabilize protein structure": "",
  "A bond between sulfur and phosphorus in nucleotides": "",
  "An ionic interaction between sulfur and a metal ion cofactor": "",
  "A disulfide bridge (disulfide bond) is a strong covalent S-S bond formed by oxidation of the sulfhydryl groups of two cysteine amino acids. These bonds provide extra stability to proteins, especially those secreted outside the cell.": "",
  "What does the term 'substrate' mean in enzyme biology?": "",
  "The inhibitor that blocks enzyme function": "",
  "The cofactor that activates an enzyme": "",
  "The reactant molecule that binds to an enzyme's active site and undergoes a chemical reaction": "",
  "The product of an enzymatic reaction": "",
  "A substrate is the specific molecule upon which an enzyme acts. It binds to the enzyme's active site through complementary shape and charge, is converted to product(s), and then released.": "",
  "A cook fries an egg and notices the clear egg white turns opaque and solid. What is happening to the proteins at the molecular level, and why is this change irreversible under normal conditions?": "",
  "Heat denatures the albumin proteins, disrupting their 3D structure; the unfolded proteins then aggregate into a tangled solid mass that cannot spontaneously refold": "",
  "Water evaporates from the egg white, concentrating the proteins without changing them": "",
  "The heat converts proteins into carbohydrates, changing the egg's appearance": "",
  "The proteins are being synthesized into new, larger molecules by the heat": "",
  "Heat breaks the noncovalent bonds (hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions, ionic bonds) that maintain albumin's globular shape. The unfolded proteins expose hydrophobic R groups that aggregate into an insoluble mass, making the process practically irreversible.": "",
  "A patient with sickle cell disease has a single amino acid substitution (glutamic acid replaced by valine) in the beta-globin chain of hemoglobin. How does this one change in primary structure lead to the disease?": "",
  "The substitution prevents hemoglobin from being translated on ribosomes": "",
  "Replacing hydrophilic glutamic acid with hydrophobic valine creates a sticky patch that causes hemoglobin molecules to aggregate into fibers, distorting red blood cells into a sickle shape": "",
  "Valine destroys all four subunits of hemoglobin simultaneously": "",
  "Valine is larger than glutamic acid and blocks the active site of hemoglobin": "",
  "The E6V substitution replaces a charged, hydrophilic glutamic acid with nonpolar valine on the protein surface. This creates a hydrophobic patch that causes deoxygenated hemoglobin molecules to polymerize into rigid fibers, deforming red blood cells.": "",
  "A biotechnology company wants to produce human insulin in bacteria. They insert the human insulin gene into E. coli, but the resulting protein is misfolded and nonfunctional. A scientist suggests that chaperone proteins may be needed. Why might bacterial cells fail to fold human insulin correctly?": "",
  "Bacterial ribosomes are too large to synthesize small human proteins when considering all relevant human factors": "",
  "Bacteria cannot read human DNA codons given that prevailing human conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "Human insulin genes cannot be transcribed in bacterial cells because conventional analysis of human suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "Bacteria lack the specific chaperone proteins and post-translational processing machinery (like disulfide bond isomerase) that human cells use to fold insulin into its correct 3D conformation": "",
  "Human insulin requires specific disulfide bridges and post-translational processing for correct folding. Bacteria may lack the appropriate chaperones and enzymes (like disulfide isomerases) found in the eukaryotic endoplasmic reticulum.": "",
  "A forensic scientist uses gel electrophoresis to separate proteins from a blood sample found at a crime scene. The proteins migrate different distances through the gel. What property of proteins determines how far they travel?": "",
  "The color of the protein determines migration distance": "",
  "Proteins migrate based on how many disulfide bridges they contain": "",
  "All proteins travel the same distance regardless of size": "",
  "In SDS-PAGE, proteins are denatured and coated with SDS, so migration depends primarily on molecular weight, with smaller proteins traveling farther": "",
  "In SDS-PAGE, SDS detergent denatures proteins and gives them a uniform negative charge proportional to their length. Smaller proteins navigate the gel pores more easily and migrate farther, allowing separation by molecular weight.": "",
  "A neurobiologist is studying prion diseases like Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease. The disease is caused by a misfolded version of a normal brain protein (PrP) that induces other PrP molecules to misfold. Which concept of protein structure best explains how prions propagate?": "",
  "Prions change the DNA sequence encoding PrP in brain cells, particularly when protein considerations are weighed against competing pressures": "",
  "Prions break the peptide bonds of normal proteins due to the well-established relationship between protein trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "Prions are viruses that inject RNA into brain cells considering that the key variables involved tend to move in this direction together": "",
  "The misfolded prion protein acts as a template that converts normal PrP proteins from alpha-helical to beta-sheet-rich conformations, demonstrating that tertiary structure determines function": "",
  "Prions are misfolded proteins (rich in beta sheets instead of alpha helices) that physically contact and induce conformational changes in normal PrP proteins. This demonstrates that a protein's 3D structure is critical for its function.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical researcher discovers that a drug works by binding to the active site of a viral protease enzyme, preventing the virus from assembling new viral particles. What type of enzyme inhibition does this drug use?": "",
  "Competitive inhibition, because the drug competes with the viral protein substrate for the enzyme's active site": "",
  "Noncompetitive inhibition, because the drug changes the enzyme's shape": "",
  "Allosteric activation": "",
  "Feedback inhibition by the end product of a metabolic pathway": "",
  "Since the drug binds directly to the active site (where the substrate normally binds), it is a competitive inhibitor. It competes with the natural substrate for access to the active site, blocking the enzyme's catalytic activity.": "",
  "A student leaves a bottle of milk on the counter for several days and notices it curdles. The proteins (caseins) in the milk have aggregated. What most likely caused this protein denaturation?": "",
  "UV light from the room denatured the proteins": "",
  "The proteins spontaneously broke into individual amino acids": "",
  "Bacteria fermented lactose into lactic acid, lowering the pH and disrupting ionic and hydrogen bonds that maintained casein's structure": "",
  "Oxygen in the air oxidized the proteins into lipids": "",
  "Bacteria convert lactose to lactic acid, lowering the milk's pH. The increased acidity disrupts the electrostatic and hydrogen bond interactions that keep caseins in their native structure, causing them to denature and aggregate (curdle).": "",
  "A geneticist studies collagen deficiency in a patient with Ehlers-Danlos syndrome. Collagen is a structural protein with a triple-helix quaternary structure. If a mutation replaces glycine (the smallest amino acid) with a bulkier amino acid in one of the three chains, what is the likely effect?": "",
  "The mutation will only affect primary structure, not the protein's function": "",
  "The bulkier amino acid disrupts the tight triple-helix packing, weakening the collagen fiber and causing connective tissue fragility": "",
  "The mutation causes the cell to produce more collagen to compensate": "",
  "The protein will function normally because one amino acid change is insignificant": "",
  "Glycine's small size is essential at every third position in collagen because it fits in the crowded interior of the triple helix. A bulkier amino acid disrupts this tight arrangement, destabilizing the triple helix and weakening connective tissues.": "",
  "A researcher is developing a heat-stable enzyme for industrial laundry detergent that must work at high temperatures. She studies enzymes from thermophilic bacteria living in hot springs. What structural adaptations likely make these enzymes heat-resistant?": "",
  "Thermophilic enzymes have fewer amino acids and are therefore smaller": "",
  "Thermophilic enzymes have increased hydrophobic core packing, more salt bridges, more disulfide bonds, and other stabilizing interactions that resist thermal denaturation": "",
  "Thermophilic enzymes use RNA instead of amino acids": "",
  "Thermophilic enzymes are made of different elements than normal enzymes": "",
  "Thermophilic enzymes maintain their structure at high temperatures through increased intramolecular interactions: tighter hydrophobic core packing, more ionic interactions (salt bridges), additional disulfide bonds, and shorter surface loops that resist unfolding.": "",
  "A cell biologist discovers that the protein p53, known as the 'guardian of the genome,' is mutated in over 50% of human cancers. In normal cells, p53 activates DNA repair genes and triggers apoptosis if damage is irreparable. How does a mutation that disrupts p53's tertiary structure contribute to cancer development?": "",
  "When p53's 3D structure is disrupted, it cannot bind to DNA or activate target genes, allowing cells with damaged DNA to escape cell cycle checkpoints and continue dividing, potentially accumulating oncogenic mutations": "",
  "The mutation converts p53 into an enzyme that degrades tumor suppressor genes, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Mutated p53 speeds up the cell cycle to repair DNA faster based on the conventional understanding of how apoptosis processes interact in practice": "",
  "Mutated p53 directly causes DNA damage in cells, which is consistent with how apoptosis mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "p53 is a transcription factor whose function depends on its 3D structure to bind DNA. Mutations that disrupt its shape prevent it from activating DNA repair or apoptosis pathways, allowing damaged cells to proliferate and accumulate mutations leading to cancer.": ""
}